                                                                <div class="text">
                                                                    <div itemprop="text">
                                                                        <p>We aren&rsquo;t, and we don&rsquo;t. You are misinformed.</p>
                                                                        <p>In Britain, the word &lsquo;biscuit&rsquo; means a hard baked cookie, like a graham cracker. Since this is the normal use of this word in the UK, we don&rsquo;t automatically think of the plain scone-type baked goods for which Americans use the word &lsquo;biscuit&rsquo;. US English is a different dialect of English, and there are many words which have different meanings from U.K. English (jumper, braces, suspenders, tap etc.)</p>
                                                                        <p>What on earth makes you think we call bread rolls &lsquo;puddings&rsquo;? In the U.K., pudding is any dessert, not just the blancmange-stuff which Americans use that word for. It is correct in the U.K. to say &ldquo;I&rsquo;m having apple pie for pudding.&rdquo;.</p>
